tain a \"swap map\" and when looking up gates by inputs, we use the corrected wire names.\n\nActually, a simpler approach: since we look up gates by `(op, inputs)`, and inputs reference wire NAMES (which may be swapped outputs of upstream gates), we need to handle the indirection. The approach:\n\n- Walk bit by bit\n- For each gate found by pattern, note its ACTUAL output wire name\n- Use that actual output wire name as the input for downstream gate lookups\n- Compare actual output to EXPECTED output (z-wires, structural role)\n- Collect mismatches\n\nThis works because: when we look for the XOR gate with inputs (x01, y01), we find it regardless of what its output is named. Its actual output (whatever name it has) IS the partial sum wire for bit 1, even if the name was swapped from somewhere else. We use that actual name to find the next gate.\n\nThe only check is: does the output wire name match what it SHOULD be? For z-wires, we know exactly. For intermediate wires, the name doesn't matter as long as the structure is consistent. So we only flag:\n- z-wire outputs that don't start with 'z' at the right position\n- Non-z outputs that incorrectly have a z-name\n- OR gates (carry) whose output ended up as a z-wire when it shouldn't\n\nWait - we need to be more precise. The swaps are of output wire names between ANY two gates, not just within a bit position. So a carry wire from bit 5 could be swapped with a z-wire from bit 20.\n\n**Refined approach:** Walk the adder structure bit by bit, using actual wire names for connectivity. At each step, record what the output wire IS vs what it SHOULD be. Specifically:\n\n- z-output gates: the XOR gate that produces the final sum for bit i should output \"z{i:02d}\". If it doesn't, that output is swapped.\n- For the final carry, it should output \"z{N:02d}\".\n- For intermediate wires (partial sum, generate, propagate, carry), the names don't matter structurally - BUT if they happen to be named like a z-wire, that z-wire was sto