ome from a different gate than intended\n  // (due to swaps), but the name is consistent.\n\n  // Strategy: check each gate's output against structural rules.\n  // A gate's output is \"wrong\" if:\n  //   1. It should be a z-wire but isn't\n  //   2. It IS a z-wire but shouldn't be\n  //   3. It doesn't connect properly to expected downstream gates\n\n  // We'll use a different approach: check structural rules for each gate.\n  // Rule 1: XOR gates with x/y inputs (partial sum) should NOT output z-wires\n  //         (except bit 0 which should output z00)\n  // Rule 2: XOR gates without x/y inputs (final sum) SHOULD output z-wires\n  // Rule 3: AND gates should NOT output z-wires\n  // Rule 4: OR gates should NOT output z-wires (except the final carry -> z{N})\n  // Rule 5: For each z-wire, the gate producing it should be appropriate\n\n  // But this alone won't catch all swaps (e.g., two intermediate wires swapped).\n  // We need the structural walk too.\n\n  // Combined approach: Walk the structure using INPUT wire names to identify\n  // gate roles, then check outputs.\n\n  // The trick for walking: we need to find \"the gate that uses wire W as input\"\n  // to trace from one gate's output to the next gate.\n  // Build: wire -> list of gates that use it as input\n  const consumers = new Map<string, Gate[]>();\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    for (const w of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      if (!consumers.has(w)) consumers.set(w, []);\n      consumers.get(w)!.push(gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // For bit 0: check half adder\n  const xor0 = xorXY.get(0)!;\n  const and0 = andXY.get(0)!;\n\n  if (xor0.out !== 'z00') {\n    swapped.add(xor0.out);\n    swapped.add('z00');\n  }\n\n  // The carry wire name for bit 0 is and0.out\n  // Downstream gates reference this wire by name in their inputs\n  let carryWire = and0.out;\n\n  for (let i = 1; i < numBits; i++) {\n    const zi = `z${bitStr(i)}`;\n\n    const xorI = xorXY.get(i)!;\n    const andI = andXY.get(i)!;\n\n    // XOR(xi, yi).out = partial sum wire name\n    const partialSumWire = xorI.out;\n\n    // The partial sum wire should be used by exactly 2 downstream gates:\n    // 1. XOR(partialSum, carry) -> zi (sum)\n    // 2. AND(partialSum, carry) -> propagate\n    // The carry wire should also be used by these same 2 gates.\n\n    // Find the sum XOR gate: it uses partialSumWire as input and is a XOR\n    // But we need to distinguish it from xorI itself.\n    let sumXorGate: Gate | undefined;\n    let propAndGate: Gate | undefined;\n\n    const psConsumers = consumers.get(partialSumWire) || [];\n    for (const g of psConsumers) {\n      if (g.op === 'XOR') sumXorGate = g;\n      if (g.op === 'AND') propAndGate = g;\n    }\n\n    // If we can't find the sum XOR gate using partialSumWire, the partial sum\n    // wire was swapped. The gate that should consume the partial sum instead\n    // consumes a different wire (the one that was swapped with partialSumWire).\n    if (!sumXorGate) {\n      // partialSumWire (xorI.out) is swapped. The downstream XOR gate that\n      // produces zi has an input that should be partialSumWire but instead\n      // references whatever wire was swapped into xorI's output.\n      //\n      // Find it by looking at carryWire consumers: the sum XOR uses carry too.\n      const carryConsumers = consumers.get(carryWire) || [];\n      for (const g of carryConsumers) {\n        if (g.op === 'XOR') {\n          sumXorGate = g;\n          // The other input of this gate is what partialSumWire should have been\n          const correctPSWire = g.in1 === carryWire ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n          swapped.add(partialSumWire);\n          swapped.add(correctPSWire);\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // If we still can't find it via carry consumers, carry itself might be swapped\n    if (!sumXorGate) {\n      // Both partialSum and carry might be swapped, or carry is swapped\n      // This is a complex case. For now, skip.\n      // Actually: if carry wire doesn't appear in any XOR gate input,\n      // then carry was swapped. We should have detected this earlier or\n      // handle it now.\n      // TODO: handle this case\n      continue;\n    }\n\n    // Verify the sum XOR gate also uses the carry wire\n    const sumXorOtherInput = sumXorGate.in1 === partialSumWire ? sumXorGate.in2 :\n                              sumXorGate.in2 === partialSumWire ? sumXorGate.in1 :\n                              // partialSumWire was corrected above, so check both inputs\n                              sumXorGate.in1 === carryWire ? sumXorGate.in2 : sumXorGate.in1;\n\n    if (sumXorOtherInput !== carryWire) {\n      // The sum XOR gate uses a different wire instead of carry.\n      // This means carry was swapped.\n      // Actually, this could mean partialSum was swapped and we already\n      // found the gate via carry. Let's check.\n      if (sumXorGate.in1 !== carryWire && sumXorGate.in2 !== carryWire) {\n        // Neither input is carry. This shouldn't happen if we found it via carry.\n        // Skip for now.\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Check if sum XOR outputs the correct z-wire\n    if (sumXorGate.out !== zi) {\n      swapped.add(sumXorGate.out);\n      swapped.add(zi);\n    }\n\n    // Find the propagate AND gate (uses partialSum and carry as inputs)\n    if (!propAndGate) {\n      // Similar to above - if partialSumWire was swapped, we need to find\n      // the AND gate via carry consumers\n      const carryConsumers = consumers.get(carryWire) || [];\n      for (const g of carryConsumers) {\n        if (g.op === 'AND') {\n          propAndGate = g;\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // The generate wire is andI.out\n    const generateWire = andI.out;\n    // The propagate wire is propAndGate?.out\n    const propagateWire = propAndGate?.out;\n\n    // Find the OR gate: it uses generate and propagate as inputs\n    let orGate: Gate | undefined;\n\n    if (propagateWire) {\n      // Look for OR gate that uses generateWire\n      const genConsumers = consumers.get(generateWire) || [];\n      for (const g of genConsumers) {\n        if (g.op === 'OR') {\n          orGate = g;\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n\n      if (!orGate) {\n        // generateWire doesn't feed into any OR gate.\n        // generate was swapped with something.\n        // Look for OR gate via propagateWire\n        const propConsumers = consumers.get(propagateWire) || [];\n        for (const g of propConsumers) {\n          if (g.op === 'OR') {\n            orGate = g;\n            // The other input should be generate, but it's something else\n            const correctGenWire = g.in1 === propagateWire ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n            swapped.add(generateWire);\n            swapped.add(correctGenWire);\n            break;\n          }\n        }\n      } else {\n        // Verify the OR gate also uses propagateWire\n        const orOtherInput = orGate.in1 === generateWire ? orGate.in2 : orGate.in1;\n        if (orOtherInput !== propagateWire) {\n          // propagateWire was swapped\n          swapped.add(propagateWire);\n          swapped.add(orOtherInput);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    if (orGate) {\n      carryWire = orGate.out;\n    } else {\n      // Can't find carry - try to continue anyway\n      // This might happen if both generate and propagate were swapped\n      break;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Final carry should be z{numBits}\n  const finalZ = `z${bitStr(numBits)}`;\n  if (carryWire !== finalZ) {\n    swapped.add(carryWire);\n    swapped.add(finalZ);\n  }\n\n  return [...swapped].sort();\n}","newString":"/**\n * Find the 8 wires involved in 4 swap pairs in a broken ripple-carry adder circuit.\n * Returns sorted array of the 8 wire names.\n *\n * The algorithm checks each gate against structural rules of a ripple-carry adder.\n * Only OUTPUT wire names are swapped, so we can identify each gate's role by its\n * (op, inputs) and then verify the output name is appropriate for that role.\n *\n * We use two complementary strategies:\n * 1. Gate role classification: identify what role each gate plays and check output\n * 2. Forward structural walk: trace carry chain bit-by-bit, detecting mismatches\n */\nexport function findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[] {\n  const swapped = new Set<string>();\n\n  function bitStr(n: number): string {\n    return n.toString().padStart(2, '0');\n  }\n\n  // Determine number of input bits\n  let maxBit = 0;\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    for (const wire of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      const match = wire.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n      if (match) {\n        maxBit = Math.max(maxBit, parseInt(match[1], 10));\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  const numBits = maxBit + 1;\n\n  // Index: (op, sorted inputs) -> gate\n  const gateBySignature = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  // Index: output wire -> gate\n  const gateByOutput = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  // Index: wire -> gates using it as input\n  const consumers = new Map<string, Gate[]>();\n\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    const inputs = [gate.in1, gate.in2].sort();\n    gateBySignature.set(`${gate.op}:${inputs[0]}:${inputs[1]}`, gate);\n    gateByOutput.set(gate.out, gate);\n\n    for (const w of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      if (!consumers.has(w)) consumers.set(w, []);\n      consumers.get(w)!.push(gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  function findGate(op: string, w1: string, w2: string): Gate | undefined {\n    const inputs = [w1, w2].sort();\n    return gateBySignature.get(`${op}:${inputs[0]}:${inputs[1]}`);\n  }\n\n  function getConsumers(wire: string, op: string): Gate[] {\n    return (consumers.get(wire) || []).filter(g => g.op === op);\n  }\n\n  // Identify first-level gates (those with x/y inputs)\n  const xorXY = new Map<number, Gate>();\n  const andXY = new Map<number, Gate>();\n\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    const inputs = [gate.in1, gate.in2].sort();\n    const xMatch = inputs[0].match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n    const yMatch = inputs[1].match(/^y(\\d+)$/);\n    if (xMatch && yMatch && xMatch[1] === yMatch[1]) {\n      const bit = parseInt(xMatch[1], 10);\n      if (gate.op === 'XOR') xorXY.set(bit, gate);\n      else if (gate.op === 'AND') andXY.set(bit, gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Walk bit by bit.\n  // We track carry as the OUTPUT wire of the previous bit's carry gate.\n  // Downstream gates reference this carry wire by name in their inputs.\n  // If carry was swapped, those references still use the OLD name.\n  // So we need to handle carry tracking carefully.\n\n  const xor0 = xorXY.get(0)!;\n  const and0 = andXY.get(0)!;\n\n  // Bit 0: half adder\n  if (xor0.out !== 'z00') {\n    swapped.add(xor0.out);\n    swapped.add('z00');\n  }\n\n  // carryWire = the OUTPUT name of the carry-producing gate.\n  // In a correct circuit, downstream gates reference this name in their inputs.\n  // After a swap, the carry gate has a different output name, and downstream\n  // gates still reference the old name. We detect this disconnect.\n  let carryWire = and0.out;\n\n  for (let i = 1; i < numBits; i++) {\n    const zi = `z${bitStr(i)}`;\n    const xorI = xorXY.get(i)!;\n    const andI = andXY.get(i)!;\n    const partialSumWire = xorI.out;\n\n    // Find the sum XOR gate: XOR(partialSum, carry) -> zi\n    // We try to find it by signature first (fast path).\n    let sumXorGate = findGate('XOR', partialSumWire, carryWire);\n\n    if (sumXorGate) {\n      // Fast path: both wires are correct. Check output.\n      if (sumXorGate.out !== zi) {\n        swapped.add(sumXorGate.out);\n        swapped.add(zi);\n      }\n    } else {\n      // The sum XOR gate can't be found with (partialSum, carry).\n      // Either partialSum or carry was swapped (their output wire names changed).\n      //\n      // Key insight: in the input graph, the downstream gates still reference\n      // the ORIGINAL wire names. So the sum XOR gate references the old\n      // carry/partialSum wire names.\n      //\n      // If carry was swapped: the OR gate at bit i-1 outputs a different name\n      // (carryWire), but the sum XOR gate's input still says the old carry name.\n      // If partialSum was swapped: xorI.out has a different name, but the sum\n      // XOR gate's input still says the old partialSum name.\n      //\n      // Strategy: look at consumers of partialSumWire and carryWire to find\n      // the sum XOR gate.\n\n      // Check if partialSumWire is consumed by any XOR gate\n      const psXorConsumers = getConsumers(partialSumWire, 'XOR');\n      // Check if carryWire is consumed by any XOR gate\n      const carryXorConsumers = getConsumers(carryWire, 'XOR');\n\n      if (psXorConsumers.length > 0) {\n        // partialSumWire IS consumed by a XOR gate.\n        // That gate's other input should be carry but it references the old carry name.\n        sumXorGate = psXorConsumers[0];\n        const otherInput = sumXorGate.in1 === partialSumWire ? sumXorGate.in2 : sumXorGate.in1;\n        // otherInput is the old carry name. carryWire is the new carry name.\n        // The carry was swapped: old name (otherInput) <-> new name (carryWire)\n        swapped.add(carryWire);\n        swapped.add(otherInput);\n        carryWire = otherInput; // Fix carry for current bit\n      } else if (carryXorConsumers.length > 0) {\n        // carryWire IS consumed by a XOR gate, but partialSumWire isn't.\n        // partialSum was swapped.\n        sumXorGate = carryXorConsumers[0];\n        const otherInput = sumXorGate.in1 === carryWire ? sumXorGate.in2 : sumXorGate.in1;\n        // otherInput is the old partialSum name. partialSumWire is the new name.\n        swapped.add(partialSumWire);\n        swapped.add(otherInput);\n        // Note: for AND(partialSum, carry) lookup later, we need the old partialSum name\n        // since that's what the AND gate references in its inputs.\n        // We'll handle this below.\n      }\n\n      if (sumXorGate) {\n        if (sumXorGate.out !== zi) {\n          swapped.add(sumXorGate.out);\n          swapped.add(zi);\n        }\n      } else {\n        continue;\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Find the propagate AND gate: AND(partialSum, carry) -> propagate\n    // Use the INPUT-side wire names (what the gate actually references)\n    // These are the wire names that appear as inputs in the gate definition.\n    // If partialSum was swapped, the AND gate references the OLD partialSum name.\n    // If carry was swapped, the AND gate references the OLD carry name.\n    // We identify the AND gate from the sum XOR gate's inputs (since they share the same inputs).\n    const sumIn1 = sumXorGate!.in1;\n    const sumIn2 = sumXorGate!.in2;\n    const propAndGate = findGate('AND', sumIn1, sumIn2);\n\n    // The generate wire is andI.out\n    const generateWire = andI.out;\n    const propagateWire = propAndGate?.out;\n\n    // Find the OR gate: OR(generate, propagate) -> carry_out\n    let orGate: Gate | undefined;\n\n    if (propagateWire) {\n      orGate = findGate('OR', generateWire, propagateWire);\n\n      if (!orGate) {\n        // One of generate or propagate was swapped.\n        // Check which one is consumed by an OR gate.\n        const genOrConsumers = getConsumers(generateWire, 'OR');\n        const propOrConsumers = getConsumers(propagateWire, 'OR');\n\n        if (genOrConsumers.length > 0) {\n          orGate = genOrConsumers[0];\n          const otherInput = orGate.in1 === generateWire ? orGate.in2 : orGate.in1;\n          swapped.add(propagateWire);\n          swapped.add(otherInput);\n        } else if (propOrConsumers.length > 0) {\n          orGate = propOrConsumers[0];\n          const otherInput = orGate.in1 === propagateWire ? orGate.in2 : orGate.in1;\n          swapped.add(generateWire);\n          swapped.add(otherInput);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    if (orGate) {\n      carryWire = orGate.out;\n    } else {\n      break;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Final carry should be z{numBits}\n  const finalZ = `z${bitStr(numBits)}`;\n  if (carryWire !== finalZ) {\n    swapped.add(carryWire);\n    swapped.add(finalZ);\n  }\n\n  return [...swapped].sort();\n}","originalFile":"export interface Gate {\n  op: 'AND' | 'OR' | 'XOR';\n  in1: string;\n  in2: string;\n  out: string;\n}\n\n/**\n * Simulate a logic gate circuit given initial wire values.\n * Returns the final value of every wire (inputs + computed).\n */\nexport function simulate(\n  gates: Gate[],\n  inputs: Record<string, number>\n): Record<string, number> {\n  const wireValues: Record<string, number> = { ...inputs };\n\n  // Map each wire to gates that depend on it as input\n  const dependents = new Map<string, Gate[]>();\n  // Track how many inputs are ready for each gate\n  const readyCount = new Map<Gate, number>();\n\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    readyCount.set(gate, 0);\n    for (const inputWire of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      if (!dependents.has(inputWire)) {\n        dependents.set(inputWire, []);\n      }\n      dependents.get(inputWire)!.push(gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Initialize ready counts from known wire values\n  const queue: Gate[] = [];\n  for (const wire of Object.keys(wireValues)) {\n    const deps = dependents.get(wire);\n    if (deps) {\n      for (const gate of deps) {\n        const count = readyCount.get(gate)! + 1;\n        readyCount.set(gate, count);\n        if (count === 2) {\n          queue.push(gate);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Process gates in dependency order\n  while (queue.length > 0) {\n    const gate = queue.pop()!;\n    const a = wireValues[gate.in1];\n    const b = wireValues[gate.in2];\n\n    let result: number;\n    switch (gate.op) {\n      case 'AND':\n        result = a & b;\n        break;\n      case 'OR':\n        result = a | b;\n        break;\n      case 'XOR':\n        result = a ^ b;\n        break;\n    }\n\n    wireValues[gate.out] = result;\n\n    // Notify downstream gates\n    const deps = dependents.get(gate.out);\n    if (deps) {\n      for (const dep of deps) {\n        const count = readyCount.get(dep)! + 1;\n        readyCount.set(dep, count);\n        if (count === 2) {\n          queue.push(dep);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n\n  return wireValues;\n}\n\n/**\n * Find the 8 wires involved in 4 swap pairs in a broken ripple-carry adder circuit.\n * Returns sorted array of the 8 wire names.\n *\n * Algorithm: Check each gate's structural role in the ripple-carry adder and\n * validate that its output wire name is consistent with that role.\n *\n * Key insight: swaps only change OUTPUT wire names. Gate inputs and operations\n * are unchanged. We use input wire names to trace the circuit structure, since\n * those are preserved. When an output is swapped, downstream gates still\n * reference the original wire name in their inputs.\n */\nexport function findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[] {\n  const swapped = new Set<string>();\n\n  // Index gate by output wire name\n  const gateByOutput = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    gateByOutput.set(gate.out, gate);\n  }\n\n  function bitStr(n: number): string {\n    return n.toString().padStart(2, '0');\n  }\n\n  // Determine number of input bits\n  let maxBit = 0;\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    for (const wire of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      const match = wire.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n      if (match) {\n        maxBit = Math.max(maxBit, parseInt(match[1], 10));\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  const numBits = maxBit + 1;\n\n  // Classify each gate's role based on its inputs\n  // In a correct ripple-carry adder, each gate has a specific role.\n  // We identify roles by looking at input patterns:\n  //\n  // Bit 0 (half adder):\n  //   XOR(x00, y00) -> z00           [sum]\n  //   AND(x00, y00) -> carry_wire    [carry_gen]\n  //\n  // Bit i >= 1 (full adder):\n  //   XOR(xi, yi) -> partial_sum     [partial_xor]\n  //   XOR(partial_sum, carry_in) -> zi [sum] -- but we identify this differently\n  //   AND(xi, yi) -> generate        [generate]\n  //   AND(partial_sum, carry_in) -> propagate [propagate]\n  //   OR(generate, propagate) -> carry_out [carry_or]\n\n  // First: identify all \"first-level\" gates (those with x/y inputs)\n  // These gates are XOR(xi,yi) and AND(xi,yi)\n  const xorXY = new Map<number, Gate>(); // bit -> gate\n  const andXY = new Map<number, Gate>(); // bit -> gate\n\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    const xMatch1 = gate.in1.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n    const yMatch1 = gate.in2.match(/^y(\\d+)$/);\n    const xMatch2 = gate.in2.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n    const yMatch2 = gate.in1.match(/^y(\\d+)$/);\n\n    let bit = -1;\n    if (xMatch1 && yMatch1 && xMatch1[1] === yMatch1[1]) {\n      bit = parseInt(xMatch1[1], 10);\n    } else if (xMatch2 && yMatch2 && xMatch2[1] === yMatch2[1]) {\n      bit = parseInt(xMatch2[1], 10);\n    }\n\n    if (bit >= 0) {\n      if (gate.op === 'XOR') xorXY.set(bit, gate);\n      else if (gate.op === 'AND') andXY.set(bit, gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Now trace through the circuit using INPUT wire names.\n  // The carry wire for each bit is identified by following the input references.\n  //\n  // In the original (correct) circuit:\n  //   - The carry output of bit 0 is AND(x00,y00).out\n  //   - The carry output of bit i is OR(gen_i, prop_i).out\n  //   - gen_i = AND(xi, yi).out\n  //   - prop_i = AND(partial_sum_i, carry_{i-1}).out\n  //   - partial_sum_i = XOR(xi, yi).out\n  //\n  // After swaps, the .out names might be wrong, but the gate input references\n  // still point to the \"old\" wire names. So we follow via input references.\n\n  // For the trace, we track the WIRE NAME that carries each signal.\n  // Since swaps only change output names, the wire that a downstream gate\n  // references in its input is the ACTUAL wire name in the circuit.\n  // The signal on that wire might come from a different gate than intended\n  // (due to swaps), but the name is consistent.\n\n  // Strategy: check each gate's output against structural rules.\n  // A gate's output is \"wrong\" if:\n  //   1. It should be a z-wire but isn't\n  //   2. It IS a z-wire but shouldn't be\n  //   3. It doesn't connect properly to expected downstream gates\n\n  // We'll use a different approach: check structural rules for each gate.\n  // Rule 1: XOR gates with x/y inputs (partial sum) should NOT output z-wires\n  //         (except bit 0 which should output z00)\n  // Rule 2: XOR gates without x/y inputs (final sum) SHOULD output z-wires\n  // Rule 3: AND gates should NOT output z-wires\n  // Rule 4: OR gates should NOT output z-wires (except the final carry -> z{N})\n  // Rule 5: For each z-wire, the gate producing it should be appropriate\n\n  // But this alone won't catch all swaps (e.g., two intermediate wires swapped).\n  // We need the structural walk too.\n\n  // Combined approach: Walk the structure using INPUT wire names to identify\n  // gate roles, then check outputs.\n\n  // The trick for walking: we need to find \"the gate that uses wire W as input\"\n  // to trace from one gate's output to the next gate.\n  // Build: wire -> list of gates that use it as input\n  const consumers = new Map<string, Gate[]>();\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    for (const w of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      if (!consumers.has(w)) consumers.set(w, []);\n      consumers.get(w)!.push(gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // For bit 0: check half adder\n  const xor0 = xorXY.get(0)!;\n  const and0 = andXY.get(0)!;\n\n  if (xor0.out !== 'z00') {\n    swapped.add(xor0.out);\n    swapped.add('z00');\n  }\n\n  // The carry wire name for bit 0 is and0.out\n  // Downstream gates reference this wire by name in their inputs\n  let carryWire = and0.out;\n\n  for (let i = 1; i < numBits; i++) {\n    const zi = `z${bitStr(i)}`;\n\n    const xorI = xorXY.get(i)!;\n    const andI = andXY.get(i)!;\n\n    // XOR(xi, yi).out = partial sum wire name\n    const partialSumWire = xorI.out;\n\n    // The partial sum wire should be used by exactly 2 downstream gates:\n    // 1. XOR(partialSum, carry) -> zi (sum)\n    // 2. AND(partialSum, carry) -> propagate\n    // The carry wire should also be used by these same 2 gates.\n\n    // Find the sum XOR gate: it uses partialSumWire as input and is a XOR\n    // But we need to distinguish it from xorI itself.\n    let sumXorGate: Gate | undefined;\n    let propAndGate: Gate | undefined;\n\n    const psConsumers = consumers.get(partialSumWire) || [];\n    for (const g of psConsumers) {\n      if (g.op === 'XOR') sumXorGate = g;\n      if (g.op === 'AND') propAndGate = g;\n    }\n\n    // If we can't find the sum XOR gate using partialSumWire, the partial sum\n    // wire was swapped. The gate that should consume the partial sum instead\n    // consumes a different wire (the one that was swapped with partialSumWire).\n    if (!sumXorGate) {\n      // partialSumWire (xorI.out) is swapped. The downstream XOR gate that\n      // produces zi has an input that should be partialSumWire but instead\n      // references whatever wire was swapped into xorI's output.\n      //\n      // Find it by looking at carryWire consumers: the sum XOR uses carry too.\n      const carryConsumers = consumers.get(carryWire) || [];\n      for (const g of carryConsumers) {\n        if (g.op === 'XOR') {\n          sumXorGate = g;\n          // The other input of this gate is what partialSumWire should have been\n          const correctPSWire = g.in1 === carryWire ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n          swapped.add(partialSumWire);\n          swapped.add(correctPSWire);\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // If we still can't find it via carry consumers, carry itself might be swapped\n    if (!sumXorGate) {\n      // Both partialSum and carry might be swapped, or carry is swapped\n      // This is a complex case. For now, skip.\n      // Actually: if carry wire doesn't appear in any XOR gate input,\n      // then carry was swapped. We should have detected this earlier or\n      // handle it now.\n      // TODO: handle this case\n      continue;\n    }\n\n    // Verify the sum XOR gate also uses the carry wire\n    const sumXorOtherInput = sumXorGate.in1 === partialSumWire ? sumXorGate.in2 :\n                              sumXorGate.in2 === partialSumWire ? sumXorGate.in1 :\n                              // partialSumWire was corrected above, so check both inputs\n                              sumXorGate.in1 === carryWire ? sumXorGate.in2 : sumXorGate.in1;\n\n    if (sumXorOtherInput !== carryWire) {\n      // The sum XOR gate uses a different wire instead of carry.\n      // This means carry was swapped.\n      // Actually, this could mean partialSum was swapped and we already\n      // found the gate via carry. Let's check.\n      if (sumXorGate.in1 !== carryWire && sumXorGate.in2 !== carryWire) {\n        // Neither input is carry. This shouldn't happen if we found it via carry.\n        // Skip for now.\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Check if sum XOR outputs the correct z-wire\n    if (sumXorGate.out !== zi) {\n      swapped.add(sumXorGate.out);\n      swapped.add(zi);\n    }\n\n    // Find the propagate AND gate (uses partialSum and carry as inputs)\n    if (!propAndGate) {\n      // Similar to above - if partialSumWire was swapped, we need to find\n      // the AND gate via carry consumers\n      const carryConsumers = consumers.get(carryWire) || [];\n      for (const g of carryConsumers) {\n        if (g.op === 'AND') {\n          propAndGate = g;\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    // The generate wire is andI.out\n    const generateWire = andI.out;\n    // The propagate wire is propAndGate?.out\n    const propagateWire = propAndGate?.out;\n\n    // Find the OR gate: it uses generate and propagate as inputs\n    let orGate: Gate | undefined;\n\n    if (propagateWire) {\n      // Look for OR gate that uses generateWire\n      const genConsumers = consumers.get(generateWire) || [];\n      for (const g of genConsumers) {\n        if (g.op === 'OR') {\n          orGate = g;\n          break;\n        }\n      }\n\n      if (!orGate) {\n        // generateWire doesn't feed into any OR gate.\n        // generate was swapped with something.\n        // Look for OR gate via propagateWire\n        const propConsumers = consumers.get(propagateWire) || [];\n        for (const g of propConsumers) {\n          if (g.op === 'OR') {\n            orGate = g;\n            // The other input should be generate, but it's something else\n            const correctGenWire = g.in1 === propagateWire ? g.in2 : g.in1;\n            swapped.add(generateWire);\n            swapped.add(correctGenWire);\n            break;\n          }\n        }\n      } else {\n        // Verify the OR gate also uses propagateWire\n        const orOtherInput = orGate.in1 === generateWire ? orGate.in2 : orGate.in1;\n        if (orOtherInput !== propagateWire) {\n          // propagateWire was swapped\n          swapped.add(propagateWire);\n          swapped.add(orOtherInput);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n\n    if (orGate) {\n      carryWire = orGate.out;\n    } else {\n      // Can't find carry - try to continue anyway\n      // This might happen if both generate and propagate were swapped\n      break;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Final carry should be z{numBits}\n  const finalZ = `z${bitStr(numBits)}`;\n  if (carryWire !== finalZ) {\n    swapped.add(carryWire);\n    swapped.add(finalZ);\n  }\n\n  return [...swapped].sort();\n}\n","structuredPatch":[{"oldStart":86,"oldLines":23,"newStart":86,"newLines":17,"lines":["  * Find the 8 wires involved in 4 swap pairs in a broken ripple-carry adder circuit.","  * Returns sorted array of the 8 wire names.","  *","- * Algorithm: Check each gate's structural role in the ripple-carry adder and","- * validate that its output wire name is consistent with that role.","+ * The algorithm checks each gate against structural rules of a ripple-carry adder.","+ * Only OUTPUT wire names are swapped, so we can identify each gate's role by its","+ * (op, inputs) and then verify the output name is app