+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0152ksbxdkGWQNLaJCJgsSYj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me take a step back and think about this problem from a higher level. The issue is that my approach of walking the adder structure bit-by-bit is fundamentally fragile because:\n\n1. Swapping a carry wire disconnects multiple downstream bits\n2. Swapping a partial sum wire creates ambiguity in gate identification\n3. My test cases with structured wire names create artificial cycles\n\nFor the real-world problem, wire names are arbitrary random strings (like `abc`, `qrs`, `ntg`), so the cycle issue won't occur. But the carry disconnection issue is real.\n\nLet me reconsider the problem. In the actual benchmark:\n- There are ~220 gates for a 45-bit adder\n- Random wire names for internal wires\n- Exactly 4 swap pairs (8 wires)\n\nThe approach that actually works well for this problem (and is commonly used for AoC 2024 Day 24) is based on **structural rule checking**. Instead of walking the carry chain, check each gate against rules:\n\n1. **Rule 1**: XOR gates with x/y inputs should NOT output z-wires (except z00).\n2. **Rule 2**: XOR gates without x/y inputs SHOULD output z-wires.\n3. **Rule 3**: AND gates should NOT output z-wires.\n4. **Rule 4**: OR gates should NOT output z-wires (except the final carry z_{N}).\n5. **Rule 5**: The output of an AND gate (except AND(x00,y00)) should be used as input to an OR gate.\n6. **Rule 6**: The output of a XOR gate with x/y inputs (except bit 0) should be used as input to another XOR gate and an AND gate.\n7. **Rule 7**: The output of an OR gate should be used as input to a XOR gate and an AND gate (except the final carry).\n\nLet me implement this rule-based approach instead:"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1470,"cache_read_input_tokens":103344,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1470},"output_tokens":3,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1a4f711a-8623-4fc1-9563-084b36330cf6","uuid":"81de5a84-874a-469f-ae8d-f218aebfc10b"}
+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0152ksbxdkGWQNLaJCJgsSYj","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017bjpNYvB1MhnKDeRxB3Eeq","name":"Edit","input":{"replace_all":false,"file_path":"/workspace/src/index.ts","old_string":"/**\n * Find the 8 wires involved in 4 swap pairs in a broken ripple-carry adder circuit.\n * Returns sorted array of the 8 wire names.\n *\n * The algorithm checks each gate against structural rules of a ripple-carry adder.\n * Only OUTPUT wire names are swapped, so we can identify each gate's role by its\n * (op, inputs) and then verify the output name is appropriate for that role.\n *\n * We use two complementary strategies:\n * 1. Gate role classification: identify what role each gate plays and check output\n * 2. Forward structural walk: trace carry chain bit-by-bit, detecting mismatches\n */\nexport function findSwappedWires(gates: Gate[]): string[] {\n  const swapped = new Set<string>();\n\n  function bitStr(n: number): string {\n    return n.toString().padStart(2, '0');\n  }\n\n  // Determine number of input bits\n  let maxBit = 0;\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    for (const wire of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      const match = wire.match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n      if (match) {\n        maxBit = Math.max(maxBit, parseInt(match[1], 10));\n      }\n    }\n  }\n  const numBits = maxBit + 1;\n\n  // Index: (op, sorted inputs) -> gate\n  const gateBySignature = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  // Index: output wire -> gate\n  const gateByOutput = new Map<string, Gate>();\n  // Index: wire -> gates using it as input\n  const consumers = new Map<string, Gate[]>();\n\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    const inputs = [gate.in1, gate.in2].sort();\n    gateBySignature.set(`${gate.op}:${inputs[0]}:${inputs[1]}`, gate);\n    gateByOutput.set(gate.out, gate);\n\n    for (const w of [gate.in1, gate.in2]) {\n      if (!consumers.has(w)) consumers.set(w, []);\n      consumers.get(w)!.push(gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  function findGate(op: string, w1: string, w2: string): Gate | undefined {\n    const inputs = [w1, w2].sort();\n    return gateBySignature.get(`${op}:${inputs[0]}:${inputs[1]}`);\n  }\n\n  function getConsumers(wire: string, op: string): Gate[] {\n    return (consumers.get(wire) || []).filter(g => g.op === op);\n  }\n\n  // Identify first-level gates (those with x/y inputs)\n  const xorXY = new Map<number, Gate>();\n  const andXY = new Map<number, Gate>();\n\n  for (const gate of gates) {\n    const inputs = [gate.in1, gate.in2].sort();\n    const xMatch = inputs[0].match(/^x(\\d+)$/);\n    const yMatch = inputs[1].match(/^y(\\d+)$/);\n    if (xMatch && yMatch && xMatch[1] === yMatch[1]) {\n      const bit = parseInt(xMatch[1], 10);\n      if (gate.op === 'XOR') xorXY.set(bit, gate);\n      else if (gate.op === 'AND') andXY.set(bit, gate);\n    }\n  }\n\n  // Walk bit by bit.\n  // We track carry as the OUTPUT wire of the previous bit's carry gate.\n  // Downstream gates reference this carry wire by name in their inputs.\n  // If carry was swapped, those references still use the OLD name.\n  // So we need to handle carry tracking carefully.\n\n  const xor0 = xorXY.get(0)!;\n  const and0 = andXY.get(0)!;\n\n  // Bit 0: half adder\n  if (xor0.out !== 'z00') {\n    swapped.add(xor0.out);\n    swapped.add('z00');\n  }\n\n  // carryWire = the OUTPUT name of the carry-producing gate.\n  // In a correct circuit, downstream gates reference this name in their inputs.\n  // After a swap, the carry gate has a different output name, and downstream\n  // gates still reference the old name. We detect this disconnect.\n  let carryWire = and0.out;\n\n  for (let i = 1; i < numBits; i++) {\n    const zi = `z${bitStr(i)}`;\n    const xorI = xorXY.get(i)!;\n    const andI = andXY.get(i)!;\n    const partialSumWire = xorI.out;\n\n    // Find the sum XOR gate: XOR(partialSum, carry) -> zi\n    // We try to find it by signature first (fast path).\n    let sumXorGate = findGate('XOR', partialSumWire, carryWire);\n\n    if (sumXorGate) {\n      // Fast path: both wires are correct. Check output.\n      if (sumXorGate.out !== zi) {\n        swapped.add(sumXorGate.out);\n        swapped.add(zi);\n      }\n    } else {\n      // The sum XOR gate can't be found with (partialSum, carry).\n      // Either partialSum or carry was swapped (their output wire names changed).\n      //\n      // The sum XOR gate still exists with its original input wire names.\n      // We find it by looking at consumers of partialSumWire or carryWire.\n      //\n      // Key constraint: the sum XOR gate for bit i has a corresponding AND gate\n      // with the SAME pair of inputs (the propagate AND gate). We use this\n      // to validate candidates.\n\n      const carryXorConsumers = getConsumers(carryWire, 'XOR');\n      const psXorConsumers = getConsumers(partialSumWire, 'XOR');\n\n      // Collect all candidate XOR gates (excluding first-level x/y gates)\n      const candidates: Gate[] = [];\n      for (const g of [...carryXorConsumers, ...psXorConsumers]) {\n        if (/^[xy]\\d+$/.test(g.in1) || /^[xy]\\d+$/.test(g.in2)) continue;\n        if (!candidates.includes(g)) candidates.push(g);\n      }\n\n      // Find the candidate that belongs to THIS bit position.\n      // The sum XOR for bit i should have one input that is the output of\n      // XOR(xi, yi) — i.e., one input should be `partialSumWire` OR should be\n      // the output of the first-level XOR gate for bit i (if partialSum was swapped,\n      // the input still references the OLD name, which traces back to xorI).\n      //\n      // We verify by checking: one of the candidate's inputs should be produced\n      // by xorI (the first-level XOR for this bit), even if the wire name differs.\n      for (const candidate of candidates) {\n        const matchingAnd = findGate('AND', candidate.in1, candidate.in2);\n        if (!matchingAnd) continue;\n\n        // Check if one input traces back to 