pagate\n        // (from AND(partial_sum, carry)). After swap, the generate input might\n        // come from a different gate. But the OR gate's input wire NAME is the\n        // original name. Since we're looking for the last OR gate, and we know\n        // its other input (the propagate) comes from AND(t_{N-1}, c_{N-2}),\n        // we can search for the OR gate that has an input matching the propagate.\n\n        // Actually, the simplest approach: find the OR gate where one input is\n        // the wire name that was ORIGINALLY lastAndGate's output. We don't know\n        // the original name, but we know it was swapped with the current name.\n        // Since the current name (lastAndGate.out) is flagged, the original name\n        // is the swap partner. But we don't know the partner yet — that's what\n        // we're trying to find!\n\n        // Break the circularity: look for OR gates that have an input produced by\n        // a non-AND gate (which indicates the input wire was swapped from an AND).\n        for (const g of gates) {\n          if (g.op !== 'OR') continue;\n          // Check if one input's producer is NOT an AND gate (meaning it was swapped)\n          // AND the other input IS from an AND gate (the propagate, likely unchanged)\n          const p1 = producer.get(g.in1);\n          const p2 = producer.get(g.in2);\n\n          // At least one input should be from an AND gate\n          // In the last bit: one from AND(x,y) [generate], one from AND(t,c) [propagate]\n          // After swap: one might come from a non-AND gate\n\n          // Check if one of the inputs is from AND(x_{N-1}, y_{N-1}) originally.\n          // The OR gate's input wire name is the ORIGINAL output of that AND gate.\n          // If the AND gate's current output is different (swapped), the input\n          // wire now comes from a different gate.\n\n          // Check: does this OR gate have an input that was SUPPOSED to come from\n          // the last AND gate? W